A literal is a constant value that appears directly in a program.

10.1. Integer Literals
An integer literal can be assigned to an integer variable as long as it can fit into the variable.
Example:
	int numberOfYears = 34;
	double weight = 0.305;

10.2. Floating-Point Literals
A Floating-Point Literals is treated as a double type value. You can make a number a float by appending the letter f or F, and you can make a double by appending the letter d or D.

EXAMPLE: FloatingPointLiterals

10.3. Scientific Notation
Floating-Point literals can be written in scientific notation in the form of a x 10b.

